From: Esod <psvita-port>
Subject: [PATCH] r_opengl: check malloc() results in the DrawPolygon batching arrays

When the batching arrays are full, DrawPolygon doubles them:

	polygonArrayAllocSize *= 2;
	new_array = malloc(polygonArrayAllocSize * sizeof(PolygonArrayEntry));
	memcpy(new_array, polygonArray, polygonArraySize * sizeof(...));   /* <-- */
	...
	polygonIndexArray = malloc(polygonArrayAllocSize * sizeof(unsigned int));

None of these mallocs are checked. Under memory pressure the memcpy (or
the next write through polygonArray / polygonIndexArray) goes through a
NULL pointer.

Two things make this worth fixing beyond the obvious:

1. The crash lands *in the renderer*, while the actual cause is memory
   exhaustion somewhere else entirely. We spent a while chasing a phantom
   OpenGL bug on the PS Vita (data abort at `polygonArray[polygonArraySize].surf
   = *pSurf;`) before realising the heap was simply full — the renderer was
   the victim, not the culprit. A NULL check turns a mystifying data abort
   into a dropped polygon.

2. `polygonArrayAllocSize` was already doubled *before* the allocations, so
   on failure the state was left describing a buffer that does not exist.
   The patch only commits the new size once both allocations succeed.

Losing a polygon when the heap is exhausted is not great, but it is vastly
better than corrupting memory, and the frame after usually recovers.
---
 src/hardware/r_opengl/r_opengl.c | 24 ++++++++++++++++++-----
 1 file changed, 19 insertions(+), 5 deletions(-)

--- a/src/hardware/r_opengl/r_opengl.c
+++ b/src/hardware/r_opengl/r_opengl.c
@@ -2344,24 +2344,38 @@ EXPORT void HWRAPI(DrawPolygon) (FSurfaceInfo *pSurf, FOutVector *pOutVerts, FUI
 		if (polygonArraySize == polygonArrayAllocSize)
 		{
 			PolygonArrayEntry* new_array;
+			unsigned int* new_index_array;
 			// ran out of space, make new array double the size
-			polygonArrayAllocSize *= 2;
-			new_array = malloc(polygonArrayAllocSize * sizeof(PolygonArrayEntry));
+			new_array = malloc(polygonArrayAllocSize * 2 * sizeof(PolygonArrayEntry));
+			new_index_array = new_array ? malloc(polygonArrayAllocSize * 2 * sizeof(unsigned int)) : NULL;
+
+			if (!new_array || !new_index_array)
+			{
+				free(new_array);
+				free(new_index_array);
+				return; // out of memory: drop this polygon rather than corrupt memory
+			}
+
+			polygonArrayAllocSize *= 2;
 			memcpy(new_array, polygonArray, polygonArraySize * sizeof(PolygonArrayEntry));
 			free(polygonArray);
 			polygonArray = new_array;
 			// also need to redo the index array, dont need to copy it though
 			free(polygonIndexArray);
-			polygonIndexArray = malloc(polygonArrayAllocSize * sizeof(unsigned int));
+			polygonIndexArray = new_index_array;
 		}

 		while (unsortedVertexArraySize + (int)iNumPts > unsortedVertexArrayAllocSize)
 		{
 			FOutVector* new_array;
 			// need more space for vertices in unsortedVertexArray
-			unsortedVertexArrayAllocSize *= 2;
-			new_array = malloc(unsortedVertexArrayAllocSize * sizeof(FOutVector));
+			new_array = malloc(unsortedVertexArrayAllocSize * 2 * sizeof(FOutVector));
+
+			if (!new_array)
+				return; // out of memory: drop this polygon
+
+			unsortedVertexArrayAllocSize *= 2;
 			memcpy(new_array, unsortedVertexArray, unsortedVertexArraySize * sizeof(FOutVector));
 			free(unsortedVertexArray);
 			unsortedVertexArray = new_array;
 		}
